--- title: "Time series features clustering, with robust sparse k-means" author: "Raphael Saldanha" date: last-modified bibliography: references.bib --- This notebooks aims to implement the global and subset modelling, adopting a clustering strategy based on time series features extraction, with the `{tsfeatures}` package. An interesting approach to cluster time series based on feature extraction may be found on @tiano2021. We approximate this strategy by using a robust implementation of sparse $k$-means clustering [@witten2010; @kondoRobustSparseKmeans2012]. ## Packages ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} library(tidyverse) library(arrow) library(tidymodels) library(bonsai) library(finetune) library(modeltime) library(timetk) library(tsfeatures) library(sparcl) library(kableExtra) library(tictoc) library(geobr) library(DT) ``` ::: ## Load data ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} tdengue <- read_parquet(file = "../tdengue.parquet") %>% drop_na() %>% select(mun, date, starts_with("cases")) ``` ::: ::: callout-note - NA values are created when the lagged variables were calculated. The rows containing those NA values are dropped due machine learning regressors constraints. - For validation purposes, only the `cases` and `cases_lag*` covariates variables are keep. ::: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} glimpse(tdengue) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` Rows: 161,370 Columns: 9 $ mun "110002", "110002", "110002", "110002", "110002", "110002",… $ date 2011-02-06, 2011-02-13, 2011-02-20, 2011-02-27, 2011-03-06… $ cases -0.51044592, 0.07880156, 0.66804904, 0.07880156, -0.5104459… $ cases_lag1 2.43579149, -0.51044592, 0.07880156, 0.66804904, 0.07880156… $ cases_lag2 0.66804904, 2.43579149, -0.51044592, 0.07880156, 0.66804904… $ cases_lag3 0.07880156, 0.66804904, 2.43579149, -0.51044592, 0.07880156… $ cases_lag4 0.66804904, 0.07880156, 0.66804904, 2.43579149, -0.51044592… $ cases_lag5 0.66804904, 0.66804904, 0.07880156, 0.66804904, 2.43579149,… $ cases_lag6 -0.51044592, 0.66804904, 0.66804904, 0.07880156, 0.66804904… ``` ::: ::: ## Clustering This procedure goal is to cluster the municipalities considering time series features similarities. ### Prepare data Prepare the data for use with the `{tsfeatures}` package, converting the panel data to a list of `ts` objects. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} tdengue_df <- tdengue %>% arrange(mun, date) %>% select(-date) %>% nest(data = cases, .by = mun) tdengue_list <- lapply(tdengue_df$data, ts) ``` ::: ### Time series features Extract time series features. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} tsf <- tsfeatures( tslist = tdengue_list, features = c("entropy", "stability", "lumpiness", "flat_spots", "stl_features", "acf_features") ) tsf$mun <- tdengue_df$mun ``` ::: ### Robust sparse k-means clustering Cluster the municipalities based solely on the time series features. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} points <- tsf %>% select(-mun, -nperiods, -seasonal_period) %>% as.matrix() %>% scale() ``` ::: Uses $k$ from 2 to 10 for clustering. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} k_seq <- 2:10 ``` ::: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} cluster_results <- tibble() cluster_labels <- list() for(k in k_seq){ res <- RSKC::RSKC(d = points, alpha = 10/60, L1 = NULL, ncl = k) tmp <- list(list(labels = res$labels)) names(tmp) <- k cluster_labels <- append(cluster_labels, tmp) cluster_results <- bind_rows(cluster_results, tibble(k = k, wss = res$WSS)) } ``` ::: The total sum of squares is plotted. The \$k=5\$ seems to be a break point. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} ggplot(cluster_results, aes(k, wss)) + geom_line() + geom_point() + theme_bw() ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](dengue_ts_global_subset_tsfeatures_sparse_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-9-1.png){width=672} ::: ::: ### Identify municipalities and cluster id Finally, the cluster partition ID is added to the main dataset. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} cluster_ids <- tibble( mun = tdengue_df$mun, group = cluster_labels[["5"]]$labels ) ``` ::: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} tdengue <- left_join(tdengue, cluster_ids, by = "mun") ``` ::: ### Cluster sizes ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} table(cluster_ids$group) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` 1 2 3 4 5 38 92 80 84 32 ``` ::: ::: ## Train and test split Split the data into training and testing. The function `time_series_split` handles the time series, not shuffling them, and considering the panel data format, as depicted in the message about overlapping timestamps detected. The last two years data will be used as the training set. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} tdengue_split <- tdengue %>% time_series_split( date_var = date, assess = 52*2, cumulative = TRUE ) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Data is not ordered by the 'date_var'. Resamples will be arranged by `date`. ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Overlapping Timestamps Detected. Processing overlapping time series together using sliding windows. ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} tdengue_split ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` <127466/33904/161370> ``` ::: ::: #### K-folds The training set will be split into k folds. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} tdengue_split_folds <- training(tdengue_split) %>% vfold_cv(v = 5) ``` ::: ## Recipes The global and subset models training specification are called recipes. The procedure bellow creates a list of those recipes. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} recipes_list <- list() ``` ::: ### Global The global training recipe uses data from all municipalities for training the models. - The date and group variables are removed prior training - The municipality identification variable is treated as an Id variable, taking no place as a predictor in the training process ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} recipe_global <- recipe(cases ~ ., data = training(tdengue_split)) %>% step_rm(date, group) %>% update_role(mun, new_role = "id variable") recipes_list <- append(recipes_list, list(global = recipe_global)) rm(recipe_global) ``` ::: ### Groups - For each group created by the clustering process, a specific training recipe will be created. For this, the first step is to filter rows from the training set, keep only the rows belonging to the group in the loop - The date and group variables are removed prior training - The municipality identification variable is treated as an Id variable, taking no place as a predictor in the training process ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} for(g in unique(tdengue$group)){ tmp <- recipe(cases ~ ., data = training(tdengue_split)) %>% step_filter(group == !!g) %>% step_rm(date, group) %>% update_role(mun, new_role = "id variable") tmp <- list(tmp) tmp <- setNames(tmp, paste0("g", g)) recipes_list <- append(recipes_list, tmp) rm(tmp) } ``` ::: ## Regressors specification ### Random forest A Random Forest specification using the `ranger` engine. The `trees` and `min_n` hyperparameters will be tuned. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} rf_spec <- rand_forest( trees = tune(), min_n = tune() ) %>% set_engine("ranger") %>% set_mode("regression") ``` ::: ### LightGBM ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} # lgbm_spec <- boost_tree( # trees = tune(), # min_n = tune(), # tree_depth = tune() # ) %>% # set_engine("lightgbm") %>% # set_mode("regression") ``` ::: ## Workflow set This step creates a workflow set, combining the training recipes and regressors specifications. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} all_workflows <- workflow_set( preproc = recipes_list, models = list(rf = rf_spec), cross = TRUE ) ``` ::: ## Tune This step tunes the training hyperparameters of each workflow. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} doParallel::registerDoParallel() tic() race_results <- all_workflows %>% workflow_map( "tune_race_anova", seed = 345, resamples = tdengue_split_folds, grid = 10, control = control_race(parallel_over = "everything"), verbose = TRUE ) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` i 1 of 6 tuning: global_rf ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` ✔ 1 of 6 tuning: global_rf (29m 42.5s) ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` i 2 of 6 tuning: g3_rf ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` ✔ 2 of 6 tuning: g3_rf (3m 8.8s) ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` i 3 of 6 tuning: g1_rf ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` ✔ 3 of 6 tuning: g1_rf (1m 39s) ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` i 4 of 6 tuning: g4_rf ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` ✔ 4 of 6 tuning: g4_rf (4m 14.5s) ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` i 5 of 6 tuning: g2_rf ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` ✔ 5 of 6 tuning: g2_rf (5m 57.4s) ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` i 6 of 6 tuning: g5_rf ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` ✔ 6 of 6 tuning: g5_rf (37.6s) ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} toc() ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` 2721.037 sec elapsed ``` ::: ::: ## Fit Each workflow will be trained using the tuned hyperparameters, considering the RMSE metric as reference. This procedure creates a list of trained models, containing the fit results and a list of the municipalities used on the training of each workflow. The global workflow is trained with data from all municipalities and the subsets workflows are trained using the respective municipalities list given by the cluster algorithm. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} tic() trained_models <- list() for(w in unique(race_results$wflow_id)){ best_tune <- race_results %>% extract_workflow_set_result(w) %>% select_best("rmse") final_fit <- race_results %>% extract_workflow(w) %>% finalize_workflow(best_tune) %>% fit(training(tdengue_split)) mold <- extract_mold(final_fit) train_ids <- mold$extras$roles$`id variable` %>% distinct() %>% pull() %>% as.character() final_fit <- list( list( "final_fit" = final_fit, "train_ids" = train_ids ) ) final_fit <- setNames(final_fit, paste0(w)) trained_models <- append(trained_models, final_fit) } toc() ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` 410.867 sec elapsed ``` ::: ::: ## Accuracy After training each workflow, the accuracy of the models are obtained applying the fitted models on the testing set. For the global model, all municipalities are using for testing. For the subsets models, only data from the subset's municipalities are considered for testing. The RMSE metric is obtained for each workflow and municipality. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} models_accuracy <- tibble() for(t in 1:length(trained_models)){ model_tbl <- modeltime_table(trained_models[[t]][[1]]) testing_set <- testing(tdengue_split) %>% filter(mun %in% trained_models[[t]][[2]]) calib_tbl <- model_tbl %>% modeltime_calibrate( new_data = testing_set, id = "mun" ) res <- calib_tbl %>% modeltime_accuracy( acc_by_id = TRUE, metric_set = metric_set(rmse) ) res$.model_id <- word(names(trained_models[t]), 1, sep = "_") models_accuracy <- bind_rows(models_accuracy, res) } ``` ::: This plot presents the RMSE distribution across the workflows. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} ggplot(data = models_accuracy, aes(x = .model_id, y = rmse, fill = .model_desc)) + geom_boxplot() ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](dengue_ts_global_subset_tsfeatures_sparse_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-24-1.png){width=672} ::: ::: ### Breakdown ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} mun_names <- lookup_muni(code_muni = "all") %>% mutate(code_muni = substr(code_muni, 0, 6)) %>% mutate(name_muni = paste0(name_muni, ", ", abbrev_state)) %>% select(code_muni, name_muni) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Using year 2010 ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} models_accuracy %>% left_join(mun_names, by = c("mun" = "code_muni")) %>% select(.model_id, .model_desc, name_muni, rmse) %>% mutate(rmse = round(rmse, 2)) %>% arrange(.model_id, .model_desc, -rmse) %>% datatable(filter = "top") ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} models_accuracy %>% left_join(mun_names, by = c("mun" = "code_muni")) %>% select(.model_id, .model_desc, name_muni, rmse) %>% mutate(rmse = round(rmse, 2)) %>% group_by(.model_desc) %>% mutate(.model_id = case_when( .model_id != "global" ~ "cluster", .default = .model_id )) %>% pivot_wider(names_from = .model_id, values_from = rmse) %>% mutate(dif = round(global - cluster, 2)) %>% ungroup() %>% datatable(filter = "top") ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
